              </m:mrow>

            <m:mrow/>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"28" "." "69"°} {}</m:annotation>
        </m:semantics>
      </m:math>
    </para></solution>
    </exercise>

      <exercise id="fs-id1169738076492" type="problems-exercises">
        <problem id="fs-id1169737819435">
          <para id="import-auto-id1169737821286">An opal such as that shown in <link target-id="import-auto-id1169738250748"/> acts like a reflection grating with rows separated by about <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>8</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>μm</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{8`"μm"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. If the opal is illuminated normally, (a) at what angle will red light be seen and (b) at what angle will blue light be seen?</para></problem></exercise>

      <exercise id="fs-id1169737728088" type="problems-exercises">
        <problem id="fs-id1169736610953">
          <para id="import-auto-id1169737980693">At what angle does a diffraction grating produces a second-order maximum for light having a first-order maximum at <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>20</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0º</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"20" "." 0°} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1169736753368">
    <para id="import-auto-id1169737728598"><m:math>
