      <exercise id="fs-id1169738117687" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1169737831279">
          <para id="import-auto-id1169737779860">Show that a diffraction grating cannot produce a second-order maximum for a given wavelength of light unless the first-order maximum is at an angle less than <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>30</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0º</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"30" "." 0°} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
    </problem></exercise><exercise id="fs-id1169738060610" type="problems-exercises">
        <problem id="fs-id1169737821807">
          <para id="import-auto-id1169738145808">If a diffraction grating produces a first-order maximum for the shortest wavelength of visible light at <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>30</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0º</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"30" "." 0°} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, at what angle will the first-order maximum be for the longest wavelength of visible light?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1169737073524">
